00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:17.160
I don't mean mud like the kind your dog tracks in, but a MUD, or Multi-User Dungeon, which would go on to inspire modern MMORPGs.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:21.920
MUDs are text-based roleplaying games that have no graphics and only involve a few users.

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:25.860
Players type in questions or commands and the game responds with written responses.

00:01:25.860 --> 00:01:29.740
Using your imagination and pretending to see the adventure is a selling point.

00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:33.560
These games are usually fantasy-based and most were inspired by Dungeons &amp; Dragons.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:40.660
One of the most famous MUDs, called MUD, was created in the late 1970s by Roy Trubshaw on a PDP-10.

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:47.220
We mentioned that in an earlier episode because that's the same computer used for the invention of Galaxy Game, the world's first coin-operated video game.

00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:54.480
MUD was simple, with players typing in N, E, S, or W for the four main directions, and words like "attack" or "defend" to battle enemies.

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:59.940
A few years later, those simple commands were replaced with more complex sentences like, "You were eaten by a Grue!"

00:01:59.940 --> 00:02:03.480
a famous phrase that many players of the game Zork encountered time and time again.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:09.880
This popular MUD sold over 680,000 copies in the first three games in its series in the 1980s.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:16.580
These games emphasised leveling-up, exploration, and monster hunting, which would become a common theme in many future MMORPGs.

00:02:16.580 --> 00:02:20.060
But text-based games have a limited audience because people like pretty pictures

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:24.320
and in 1986, Lucasfilm Games debuted Habitat on the Commodore 64.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:31.300
This game could support up to 10,000 players, but users could only play the game at night and on weekends when the server was running.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:33.040
It's like an old cellphone plan.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:35.200
Also, players had to play by the hour.

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:36.880
It's like old long distance charges.

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:44.720
